            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mia Petrova grew up in Portland, Oregon, the beloved Korean daughter of two white academics with a Slavic surname, a childhood marked by a quiet, persistent sense of dissonance. Her parents, loving and progressive, encouraged her curiosity, but couldn't provide the mirror she needed to understand her own reflection. This undercurrent of searching for belonging became the invisible force shaping her future.\n\nHer journey sharpened at the University of Washington. In a campus group for fellow Korean adoptees, she finally found a shared language for the complex feelings of gratitude, loss, and dislocation she\u2019d carried. It was a profound turning point, illuminating a path toward a Bachelor's in Social Work. She realized her life\u2019s work would be to help others navigate the very systems and identities she was just beginning to understand herself.\n\nAfter graduation, she moved to San Francisco, drawn by its reputation as a sanctuary for outsiders and a hub of advocacy. She began as a case manager, her empathy and sharp organizational skills earning her a promotion to Program Manager for LGBTQ+ Health Services. The work is demanding, navigating bureaucracy to secure care for transgender youth and queer elders, but it is the most authentic expression of her values.\n\nNow at 38, Mia\u2019s life is woven into the fabric of the Mission District. Her mornings begin with a crowded Muni ride to her clinic, a 2.5-mile journey filled with podcasts on policy and social justice. Evenings are often spent with her partner of four years, Chloe, a graphic designer whose creative energy balances Mia\u2019s structured world. Their apartment is filled with plants, art from local queer artists, and the warmth of a chosen family. Weekends are for the Clement Street Farmers' Market or hiking the trails of the Presidio.\n\nSan Francisco is more than a city to Mia; it's the place that holds all the facets of her identity without conflict. Her dream is no longer about finding her roots, but about planting new ones. She aspires to launch a mentorship program connecting LGBTQ+ elders with youth, creating intergenerational bonds of resilience\u2014the very kind of community she once longed for, and has now learned to build herself."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe was eight, in third grade, and the substitute teacher paused for a fraction of a second after calling out \"Mia Petrova?\" His eyes scanned the room and widened slightly when they landed on her. That fleeting look of discord\u2014the Slavic name not matching the Korean face\u2014was the first time she felt like a question mark. The feeling, sharp and quiet, lodged in her chest. It wasn't about being different; it was about not making sense, and it sparked the lifelong determination to build a world where she did.\n\n2.\nAt nineteen, sitting in a sterile University of Washington classroom for the first meeting of the Korean adoptee group, a student said, \u201cYou\u2019re grateful, but you\u2019re also grieving something you never had.\u201d The air left Mia\u2019s lungs. It was the most precise, validating sentence she had ever heard, giving name to the cloud of contradiction she\u2019d lived in. In that moment of shared clarity, the shame she carried dissolved into connection, solidifying her path toward a life of advocacy.\n\n3.\nShe was 26, a new case manager in San Francisco. After weeks of battling a bureaucratic system, she finally secured emergency housing for a young, trans woman who had been sleeping in Golden Gate Park. She handed her the keys, and the woman just held them, staring, before whispering, \u201cI\u2019m safe.\u201d The profound simplicity of that statement\u2014the delivery of a basic human right\u2014cemented Mia\u2019s purpose. She wasn't just doing a job; she was providing sanctuary, the very thing she had moved to this city to find.\n\n4.\nIt was a Tuesday night four years ago, a few months into dating Chloe. Mia came home from work, her mind a tangled knot of grant proposals and client crises. She found Chloe on their apartment floor, joyfully painting a thrift store canvas a brilliant, chaotic yellow. Without a word, Chloe handed Mia a brush. In that shared, silent act of creation, Mia felt the rigid structures of her day melt away. She realized this was what balance felt like\u2014not an absence of chaos, but a partner in it.\n\n5.\nLast fall, during her morning Muni ride, she watched an elderly man with a rainbow pin on his lapel offer his seat to a young person wearing a \"They/Them\" pronoun badge. The teen smiled, a brief, shy acknowledgment that bridged a forty-year gap. The quiet exchange was electric. Mia saw her entire life's work crystallized in that small gesture of intergenerational respect. Her dream of a mentorship program wasn't just an idea anymore; it was a living, breathing possibility she saw right there on the 38 Geary."
